To solve this, we first find the prime factorization of 120.
\begin{align*}120 &= 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3 \times 5 \\
&= 2^3 \times 3^1 \times 5^1 
\end{align*}
So the least common multiple of A and B is composed of the prime factors with the greatest exponent.  In other words, there exists composition of
\begin{align*}
2^3 \times 3^a \times 5^b
\end{align*}
which is A, and
\begin{align*}
2^c \times 3^1 \times 5^1
\end{align*}
which is B, for integers a and c that are not negative. It is also given that A is three-fourths of B.
\begin{align*}
2^3 \times 3^a \times 5^b &= \frac{3}{4} \times 2^c \times 3^1 \times 5^1 \\
2^3 \times 3^a \times 5^b &= 2^{c-2} \times 3^{1+a} \times 5^{1+b}  \\
\end{align*}
For the left and right sides of the above equation to always be equal, the factors must have the same exponents, so:
\begin{align*}
3^a &= 3^{1+a} \\
\end{align*}
, which is only possible when $a = 0$, and:
\begin{align*}
5^b &= 5^{1+b} \\
\end{align*}
, which is only possible when $b = 0$, so we get the following for A and B.
\begin{align*}
2^3 \times 3^0 \times 5^0 &= 2^3 \\
2^c \times 3^1 \times 5^1 &= 2^c \times3 \times 5
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
\text{Therefore,} &\\
A &= 8 \\
B &= 30 \\
\text{And the greatest common divisor is} & \\
\gcd(30,8) &= 2
\end{align*}
